Characters.

A character is the player's persona. It bundles a sound folder, a starting stat block, and a default loadout into a named identity that the game loads when the player picks that character.

The character's stats live in a plain text info.sif file alongside the sound folder, so authoring a new character is mostly a matter of dropping audio in the right folder and writing a small text file beside it.

Sound packs and info.sif files.

Character data lives in info.sif files inside the sound pack. The full path is sounds/<pack>/characters/<character>/data/info.sif.

Each character has its own info.sif. The file is self contained: every stat the character uses is written explicitly, and anything left out falls through to a sensible default. Most stats default to zero or one, the starting weapon defaults to a fist, and the starting shield defaults to none, so a freshly authored character only needs to write the lines it actually wants to override.

The info.sif file does not list any sounds. The engine learns what audio a character has by scanning the character's own folder, matching whatever clips it finds against the names it expects (hurt, swing, jump, land, fall, heal, kill, life, lev, tel, turn, buy, break, death, inv, and so on). Drop a clip in the folder and the character plays it; remove it and the character goes silent for that event. There is nothing to wire up by hand because the folder layout is the audio configuration.

Field reference.

Every field in info.sif uses the form key=value, one per line. Missing fields fall back to the defaults shown below.

weapon type (string): The category of the starting weapon, drawn from archery, artillery, explosive, or melee. Defaults to melee. Pair this with weapon type2 to pick a specific subtype, otherwise the default fist applies.
weapon type2 (string): The subtype of the starting weapon under the chosen category, e.g. fist, knife5, AK47, rocket_launcher. Defaults to fist. The combination of weapon type and weapon type2 must point at an existing weapon folder under equipments/weapons, otherwise the weapon's stats fail to load.

attack (double): The character's flat attack bonus, added to weapon damage when computing how much damage a player swing or shot deals. Defaults to 0.
defence (double): The character's flat defence value, multiplied by three and subtracted from incoming damage before it hits health. Defaults to 0.

points (double): The starting points balance, used in the upgrade and purchase menus. Defaults to 0.

fall modifier (double): How quickly the character falls, in milliseconds per tile. Lower values make a heavier character that drops faster. Defaults to 21.

health (double): The character's starting and maximum health pool. The character starts at full health.
stamina (double): The character's starting and maximum stamina pool. The character starts at full stamina.

kills (double): How many kills the character starts with on the running counter. Almost always 0 for a new character, but useful for save imports. Defaults to 0.
lives (double): How many lives the character starts with. Each life refills health on death until the last one runs out. Defaults to 1.

level (double): The character's starting level. Most stats and unlock checks read against this. Defaults to 1.
level modifier (double): A multiplier applied to xp required for the next level. Higher numbers make leveling slower. Defaults to 1.

experience (double): The character's starting xp toward the next level. Defaults to 0.
experience modifier (double): A multiplier applied to xp gains, so a higher value makes a creature's xp drop count for more. Defaults to 1.
experience required (double): The xp required to reach the next level on the first level up. Recomputed automatically each level after that, so this only sets the very first threshold. Defaults to 1.
